b'[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48283.htm)  [Next](sbe48285.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n38\\. And on account of the absence of samadhi.\n\nIf the internal organ were the agent, it would be such even in that final\nstate of meditation, called samadhi, which is the instrument of Release. But\nthat state consists therein that the meditating being realises its difference\nfrom Prak _ri_ ti, and this is a conception which Prak _ri_ ti itself (of\nwhich the internal organ is only a modification) cannot form. The Self alone,\ntherefore, is the agent. But this would imply that the activity of the Self is\nnever at rest! Of this difficulty the next Sutra disposes.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 39. And as the carpenter, in both ways](sbe48285.htm)\n\n'